ce:section.ce:para:
The colour of the pure malachite green dye solution (control sample) is dark green. Upon irradiation of naturally available day light in the presence of marigold flower-like CQDs/ZnO nanomaterials, the colour of the solution was turned to light green after a certain time, as seen in the photograph of Fig. 12
                        . To validate the extent of dye molecular degradation, UV absorption spectra were recorded using an UV spectrophotometer. Pure malachite green dye solution has major absorption bands at 612 nm, as shown in Fig. 12 d. After 60 min of solar light irradiation, the intensity of characteristic absorption peaks reduced drastically to the minimum level in the presence of marigold flower-like CQDs/ZnO nanomaterials, as seen in Fig. 12 b and c. Illumination in the absence of ZnO materials did not result in the photocatalytic degradation of dye molecules (Fig. 12(d)). This result indicates that solar light illumination and a ZnO photocatalyst are necessary to degrade dye molecules effectively. For better understanding, the relative absorption intensity of each peak was noted with respect to the ZnO and marigold flower-like CQDs/ZnO nanomaterials photocatalytic activity displayed in Fig. 12 a and b. The dye degradation percentage was also calculated with respect to the intensity of pure malachite green dye at 612 nm before and after photocatalytic treatment (11c) and was measured to be 6.2, 81.2 %, and 100 % from pure MG dye, pure ZnO, and flower-like CQDs/ZnO nanomaterials, respectively. The photocatalytic activity of pure ZnO and flower-like CQDs/ZnO nanomaterials on the Methylene Blue (MB) dye solution was also investigated (Fig. 13
                        ).
